<HEAD>Weather Service Lifts Tropical Storm Warnings for Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to UPDATE with later position.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> moved southwest away from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> on Friday after dumping heavy rain on the island. Tropical storm warnings for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> were lifted by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The storm, moving in a clockwise loop, could make a complete circle in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> if it stays together long enough to meet with a big funnel trough located in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, forecaster <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Case </PERSON> said. `` That could cause the storm to move to the northeast in a big circle,'' Case said. But, there is a 50-50 chance the storm will dissipate before then, he said. `` We do n't see any major dramatic effect on land areas,'' he said. The system surprised forecasters by achieving tropical storm strength Thursday when its winds hit 39 mph. Rainfall reports Thursday from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> included more than 14 inches at <ORGANIZATION> Punta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Este </ORGANIZATION> on the Isle of Youth, more than seven inches in <LOCATION> Matanzas </LOCATION> and nearly five inches in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. At 10:30 p.m. EST Friday, the center of the storm was located near latitude 17.8 north, longitude 85.2 west, or about 175 miles east of <LOCATION> Belize </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s highest sustained winds were near 40 mph. The hurricane season begins June 1 and ends Nov. 30. However, hurricanes have been recorded in every month but April.
