<SECOND>AM-Fusion-Pons,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utah Officials Say Japanese Fusion Work Spawning Patent Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese researchers have duplicated recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> `` cold'' fusion experiments and are reaching for the lead in the emerging technology, one of the scientists who touched off the furor complained Friday. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> panel recently refused to back a national nuclear fusion program based on discoveries by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> electrochemist <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and a British colleague, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>. Physicists contend the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> research has been largely discredited because other experimenters have failed to fully duplicate <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>' and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>'s results. But <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said Friday that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> are making major investments in nuclear fusion research and development that could wrest leadership in the field away from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. In March, <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> said they had achieved room temperature, or `` cold'' fusion, by immersing in deuterium-rich heavy water rods of palladium inside electrically charged platinum coils. The two said the reaction yield heat equivalent to 100 times the energy needed to produce the reaction. `` They've been duplicating our experiments since late March,'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said. `` The Japanese and Indians are doing just what's obvious They're doing the research needed to find out if it's feasible or not, and they're finding it is. A bitter <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> does lose its lead in nuclear fusion research, the blame should rest squarely on the shoulders of the <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The board recently concluded there is no conclusive evidence that <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> actually produced fusion. `` We've tried to tell the country that research money is the only way to cover these -LRB- developments -RRB- properly, and its pretty obvious that's not going to get done,'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said. `` We certainly ca n't match the scope of the work that the Japanese ... are doing.'' Japanese physicists at <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Nagoya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said in the November issue of the English-language Japanese Journal of Applied Physics that fusion had occurred spontaneously between two palladium electrodes in a flask filled with deuterium gas. The Japanese said the major difference between their work and that of <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> was the use of deuterium gas instead of heavy water. However, <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> he and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> already have carried out the same experiment as the Japanese, and have applied for a patent on the procedure. Japanese researchers point out their own experiments yielded a high level of neutron emissions _ up to 20,000 times the normal background level. That is one possible indicator of a fusion reaction. Topping that, another group of researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> this week reported detecting neutron levels 2.5 million times normal levels in a cold-fusion experiment using platinum electrodes in heavy water. In addition to the Japanese and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, fusion research also reportedly is under way in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
