<HEAD>Daniel Berrigan, 22 Others Arrested in Salvador Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEVEL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshals arrested 23 people, including activist <PERSON> Jesuit </PERSON> priest <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>, who blocked elevators in a federal building Friday to protest government support for <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The arrests followed a confrontation between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> and the Rev. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagin </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> of Jesuits. <PERSON> Fagin </PERSON> was not arrested but said he supported the protest. `` I'm a Catholic and I'm sympathetic to your cause, but I ca n't allow you to break the law,'' <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> told the demonstrators just before ordering their arrest `` We are upholding our civil disobedience rights,'' said <PERSON> Fagin </PERSON>. Prior to being arrested, <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON> defended the protest to reporters. `` This is a protest salvaging our own humanity,'' he said. The protests coincided with the second day of a two-day memorial held by Jesuit-run <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for six Jesuit priests murdered recently in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. There was no violence by the 80 or so protesters. Fifteen men and eight women were handcuffed and arrested later, then were arraigned on misdemeanor obstruction charges and released without having to post bail. The demonstration at the 13-story building's eight elevators began about 12:45 p.m., capping a day of prayer, song and protest joined by numerous Jesuit leaders, nuns and local high school and college students. Among them were students from <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Berrigan </PERSON>, who began his social activism with his brother during the 1960s, is tea