<HEAD>Rocky Flats Halts Plutonium Production Indefinitely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government halted operations at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant to resolve safety questions including whether enough plutonium dust has accumulated in the pipes to cause an uncontrolled nuclear reaction. Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> announced a major management shakeup at the plant and said it would not reopen until the government and the plant's new contractor _ <ORGANIZATION> EG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ are satisfied safety concerns have been met. At a news conference at the plant, 16 miles north of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said plutonium operations had been scaled back 20 percent and would be shut down altogether in the coming days. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> acknowledged that any long-term shutdown could seriously affect the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' nuclear weapons capability. The plant is the only one of its kind in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that makes plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons. Other plants in the nuclear weapons industry that have been at least partly shut down in the last two years include the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Site </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, the plutonium processing plant at the Hanford Reservation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and the Feed Materials Production Center, a uranium plant in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Rocky Flats has been plagued by safety accusations in recent years and is the target of a federal criminal probe that so far has not resulted in indictments. Earlier this fall, <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> terminated its management agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and signed a new accord with <ORGANIZATION> EG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; G, which is scheduled to take over fully Jan. 1. After touring the plant, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said, `` Although no major hardware problems were identified by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> team, conduct of operations, standards of performance, engineering support and management structure remain deficient.'' Among the safety concerns he cited was an October report issued by a team of independent investigators which found weapon-grade plutonium in a pipe that serves as an exhaust ventilation duct at one of the plant's main buildings. Initial reports indicated there was enough plutonium present _ about 12 pounds _ to cause `` criticality,'' or a nuclear reaction, but another study found there was less plutonium in the ducts than originally thought. Both reports said there was no evidence a reaction had occurred. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the criticality issue does not pose a public safety threat. `` Nevertheless, because it is an important safety issue, I am asking EG & amp; G to independently review the report's findings and produce their own action plan,'' he said. Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON>, who was present at <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' news conference, said the decision to shut down plutonium processing at <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> shows a new commitment by <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> to safety. He added: `` It's obvious that the proof is in the pudding, and it's my job as governor of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> to make sure the citizens are safe.'' Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON>, D-Colo., who earlier called for a complete shutdown at Rocky Flats, said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> `` seems to be taking a positive, if somewhat uncertain step, but in the right direction. <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON> said it was unclear how the shutdown period at Rocky Flats would be evaluated and verified. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> admitted that <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> made major mistakes at Rocky Flats. `` We did not bring our management into the modern world and we're going to do that now,'' he said. Part of the shutdown period will be dedicated to safety training, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. He said it would be necessary to regain public trust. `` Of course we have a credibility problem. What we are trying to do now is regain it,'' he said.
