<HEAD>Perfect Gymnast Lands in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>, who vaulted gracefully into American hearts as a tiny gymnast performing airy gyrations in the 1976 Olympics, has leaped what remains of the Iron Curtain to come live in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The 28-year-old <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>, who defected from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Tuesday, flew here Friday on the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> plane `` Liberty Bell'' from <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. `` I'm very happy because I'm here in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and I wanted from long time to come here,'' she said in halting English at a news conference at <LOCATION> John </LOCATION> <LOCATION> F. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. `` I wanted to have a free life.'' <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> contacted a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Friday morning and was quickly granted refugee status, said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>. He added, `` We certainly welcome Ms. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>.'' Asked how long she had thought about defecting, she replied, `` A long time. I had it in my mind for a few years.'' <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> has traveled abroad frequently since becoming the first gymnast ever to score a perfect 10 at the Olympics. She won 21 gold medals altogether in Olympic and other international meets during her career, which earned her a life of privilege in a country that has endured chronic shortages of consumer goods for most of this decade. Her defection Tuesday to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was a blow to the hard-line government of Romanian President <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, who had named the gymnast a `` Hero of Socialist Labor'' for her athletic accomplishments. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> was held up as a role model for Romanian youth. When asked what political impact her defection will have on <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> replied: `` It's not my business.'' The refugee status means <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials believe <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> has a well-founded fear of persecution if she returns to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, where the government has rejected the reformist tide sweeping other East European countries. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> was accompanied at the news conference by a man who appeared to be translating reporters' questions for her. She introduced <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> <PERSON> Panit </PERSON> by saying: `` This is my friend who helped me to come here. I want to thank him.'' Her former gymnastics coach, <PERSON> Bela </PERSON> <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON>, left <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1981 and had encouraged <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> earlier this week to follow his example. `` I knew she was unsatisfied and unhappy about her personal situation,'' he said. `` I was very happy to know she chose freedom and decided to make this very difficult step.'' <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON> said he suspects she will be bombarded by `` business propositions.'' <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON> coached the then 14-year-old <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> during her perfect performances at the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> games. Speaking from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Friday, <PERSON> Karolyi </PERSON> said he planned to return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Sunday to meet with <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>, possibly in <LOCATION> Indianopolis </LOCATION>, headquarters of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Gymnastics Federation. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON> would be eligible to apply for permanent resident status in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in one year, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials who requested anonymity said. <PERSON> Comaneci </PERSON>, accompanied by six other Romanians, crossed the border into <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> on Tuesday and went into hiding. She reportedly told a border guard she was leaving her homeland `` for the sake of freedom.''
