<HEAD>Giant of Modern Dance Dies at 58</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON>, the dancer and choreographer of jazz - and gospel-inspired works both accessible and exhilarating, was hailed as a `` giant'' of modern dance after his death at age 58 <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON>'s unique, dynamic style introduced black American music and traditions into modern dance and helped transform it into a popular art form. He died Friday after suffering for more than a year from dyscrasia, a blood disorder. Singer <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Belafonte </PERSON>, who toured with <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> in 1958 and was his longtime friend, said <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> `` was just at the beginning of his achievements. ... He was just at the threshold of his most important creative years.'' <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> died at 4:55 p.m. at <LOCATION> Lenox </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Meg </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordean </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for his company. Blood dyscrasia is a rare disorder that affects the bone marrow and red blood cells, said <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON>'s physician, Dr. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> was a giant among American artists, a towering figure on the international dance scene,'' said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Arpino </PERSON>, artistic director of The Joffrey Ballet. The <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> American Dance Theater was founded in 1958, dedicated to the preservation and enrichment of the American modern dance heritage and the uniqueness of black cultural expression. `` He was clearly one of the giants of modern dance,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Erick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. `` But he also did more for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> blacks and American black culture in dance than any other person that I know of. `` He combined a great artistic vision of modern dance with his cultural heritage.'' As a dancer, then a choreographer, <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> was known for his innovative blend of Afro-Caribbean and modern dance, ballet and jazz, whilso drew upon the styles of <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. Sources of his inspirations included memories of black churches and honky-tonk bars he knew as a child growig up poor in a small <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town, as well as social protest, as in his 1969 `` Masekela Language,'' which dealt with being black in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Of his 19 `` Revelations,'' a celebration of black spirituapel music and small-town religion that became a modern dance, <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> once said: `` Its roots ican Negro culture, which is part of the whole heritage. ... But the dance speaks to everyone. Otherwise it would n't work <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON>'s balleappeared in the repertoires of companies include <PERSON> Joffrey </PERSON>, the American Ballet Theatre, the Pari, the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> and the Royal Danish Ballet. <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON>, who stopped dancing in 1965 to concentrate on choreography, started his troupe with seven members. Today it numbers 28, many of them graduates of the <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> American Dance Center. He was born Jan. 5, 1931, in <LOCATION> Rogers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. His mother, <PERSON> Lula </PERSON>, was 17 at the time and abandoned by her husband six months later. Mother and son earned a living picking cotton and doing domestic work. At 12, <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. He discovered ballet on a junior high p to see a performance by the Ballet Russe de <LOCATION> Monte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carlo </LOCATION>. He ban his professional career with <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>'s troupe, said toountry's first multiracial modern dance company. <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> lefhe <ORGANIZATION> Horton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> for a while to study Roman but became its director after <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>'s death in 1953. <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> created 79 ballets and also staged or choreographed for operas including <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cleopatra </PERSON>'' and <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>'s `` Mass.'' The non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Alvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ailey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> administers the dance theater; the dance center, a school for dance training which registers more than 2,500 students a year, and the <ORGANIZATION> Alvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ailey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repertory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ensemble </ORGANIZATION>. In 1988, <PERSON> Ailey </PERSON> received Kennedy Center Honors for lifetime achievement in the performing arts. He also received <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Handel </PERSON> <PERSON> Medallion </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scripps </PERSON> American Dance Festival Award, given for lifetime contribution to the field of modern dance. He is survived by his mother, <PERSON> Lula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>; his stepfather, <PERSON> Fredrick </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, and a half-brother, <PERSON> Calvin </PERSO