<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> mission to help civil war refugees fled after its office was smashed and its members were threatened. <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, the chief <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> representative here, said the mission of about 30 members was evacuated Friday `` for lack of guarantees'' and that the office will be transferred to <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. The program was administered by <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> to help people displaced by the decade-old war between leftist guerrillas and government troops and to sponsor development programs. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Escalon </LOCATION> was damaged Wednesday when guerrillas invaded it and the adjoining affluent section of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benito </LOCATION> on the city's west side. Employees inside the building were evacuated by the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, an organization similar to the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, during a lull in the fighting. Government troops entered the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office later, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said, and an inspection on Thursday, after the guerrillas pulled out of the area, showed extensive destruction. The front of the building was pocked with bullet holes, and equipment and furniture inside appeared to have been deliberately smashed, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s rightist government did not admit responsibility for the damage. But <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreiro </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s protocol chief, said he extended apologies to <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> on behalf of <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>. On Thursday, more than 240 Americans were eva