<HEAD>Vote-Buying Reported in Taiwan's First Democratic Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with early leaders and more on fraud.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two candidates who want <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to reassess its relationship with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> took early leads today in this nation's first democratic election Officials reported widespread vote-buying. Long lines of voters waited to cast ballots, and state radio reported a heavy turnout to choose legislators, municipal and county officials. Tens of thousands of police guarded polling places to prevent violence. The election was expected to mark a major step in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s march toward democracy after four decades of rule by the Nationalists, who lost a civil war to Communist forces on the Chinese mainland in 1949. It was the first election to include opposition candidates and will test the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, legalized at the end of martial law in 1987. Results were expected early Sunday. In all, 722 candidates ran in the legislative, mayoral and county races. The Nationalists can not lose all power in the election. The 256-seat Legislature and the electoral college are dominated by elderly Nationalists elected for life on the Chinese mainland in the late 1940s to support the party's claim that it is the legitimate government of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The electoral college will choose a president next year. The most contentious campaign issue involved some opposition calls for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s independence, a seditious act under <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s constitution Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has threatened to invade <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> if it declares independence. In one <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> district, candidate <PERSON> Yeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chu-lan </PERSON>, an independence activist, was among the leaders for a seat in the legislature. Mrs. <PERSON> Yeh </PERSON> is the widow of <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON> <PERSON> Nan-Rong </PERSON>, who killed himself in April to avoid a police investigation for advocating independence for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. In her campaign, Mrs. <PERSON> Yeh </PERSON> continued her husband's work and risks prosecution. Incomplete results indicated that Jaw Shau-kong, a popular Nationalist legislator, was far ahead in his <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> district. Jaw has pushed for political reform, calling for the retirement of aging legislators and negotiations with the Communist government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. In the industrial city of <LOCATION> Kaohsiung </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hsu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsiao-dan </PERSON>, a former dancer, model and painter, was behind. Ms. <PERSON> Hsu </PERSON> called for universal love and freedom in her campaign and distributed nude photos of herself. The Independence Evening News today reported large-scale distribution of `` silver bullets,'' or bribes, before campaigning ended Friday. `` Some candidates threw down big bucks,'' it said. The paper's sister publication, the Independence Morning News, was sued for libel by the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Friday after it accused the Nationalists of vote-buying. Financial officials have said cash in circulation jumped by $ 1.1 billion in the past week because of vote-buying. During balloting today several voters told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> they had sold their votes. One voter said she sold her and her husband's vote to a <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> candidate for $ 19 each. Other voters said that was the going price, although one women said she only received $ 8 for her vote. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> reported scores of cases of vote-buying and intimidation. The spokesman, <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> <PERSON> En-pao </PERSON>, said investigations were under way and that evidence had been found in several cases. He did not disclose which party was to blame. In the only report of violence, a fight broke out in the northwestern city of Hualian after opposition candidates photographed a man voting on behalf of an elderly man. State radio said the elderly man's hands were shaking so he needed help. Election officials said the case was under investigation. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s three government TV stations initially gave almost exclusive coverage to Nationalist candidates but yielded under pressure from the public. The opposition claimed the Nationalists were helped by an immense party machine that mobilized village chiefs and other politicians to secure votes. Nationalists had also been accused of sabotaging opposition office and shooting an independent candidate. The Nationalists denied the charges.
