<TEXT>
 The government released from prison two senior politicians jailed since a June 30 military coup but is keeping them under house arrest, a government source and their associates said Saturday. An official source, who refused to be further identified, confirmed a newspaper report on the disposition of <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON>, head of the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirghani </PERSON>, head of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The source would give no further details, but followers of the two said they were transferred from Kober Prison in suburban <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. Several politicians remain incarcerated at the prison, chief among them the ousted prime minister, <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Mahdi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Umma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The official newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al-Hadith </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Turabi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mirghani </PERSON> were released `` after they voiced their support for the revolution'' and the policies of the military government, which include disbanding <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s 36 political parties. `` They have not been implicated in recent communist plots aiming to undermine the revolution,'' the newspaper said. That seemed to indicate the ruling junta is implicating el-Mahdi and <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nugud </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, both still in prison, in a week-long strike by doctors. The government has blamed communists for the illegal strike. In addition to the parties, coup leader Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Bashir </PERSON> disbanded all the country's professional associations and trade unions. He jailed most senior government officials and vowed to try them on charges of political and economic corruption. Only a handful have been put on trial. The government says about 20 officials remain in detention, but informed sources put the figure at close to 100.
