<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has called on the new Bulgarian leadership to clear up the murder of <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Markov </PERSON>, the Bulgarian defector killed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> 11 years ago by poison injected through the tip of an umbrella. Foreign Office Minister <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldegrave </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> on Friday that the hard-line Bulgarian government led by <PERSON> Todor </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>, which was toppled Nov. 10, was `` the instigator'' of the murder. With a new government led by <PERSON> Petur </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> now in power, he said, the truth about <PERSON> Markov </PERSON>'s murder must be told. <PERSON> Annabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Markov </PERSON>, the defector's widow, was quoted Saturday as telling The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> she hoped the reforms sweeping <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> would help reveal the truth about her husband's death `` I have always believed evil does not go unpunished. There is real hope now that my husband's killer may be tracked down,'' she was quoted as saying. Mrs. <PERSON> Markov </PERSON> is convinced the Bulgarian secret police have a file on her husband, The Times said. <PERSON> Markov </PERSON> defected in 1969 and received death threats after broadcasting a series of programs in 1977 attacking <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s Communist government on the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> world service He was murdered on a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> street in 1978.
