<HEAD>The Month That Ended An Era ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR's NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Smale </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> chief of bureau in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, has covered the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for a decade.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The panic in the eyes of a man grabbed by riot police. Shabby East German Trabants and sleek West German Mercedes side by side on the Kurfuerstendamm in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> after the Berlin Wall crumbled. The explosion of joy in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> when the hated leaders that suppressed the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Spring reforms 20 years ago had to step down. Those are some of the lasting images of a turbulent month that ended an era in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Millions of people demanded a say in politics and took their fear, their courage and their joy into the streets. Here are some images of that breathtaking month: Oct. 28: Beloved <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, city of a thousand spires, marred again by hundreds of riot police hounding peaceful pro-democracy demonstrators down alleys and sidestreets. Wenceslas Square, a tree-lined boulevard at the heart of the city, resembles a police camp. A hapless Pole tries to explain to a police officer he is on the square by mistake. Suddenly, a riot policeman charges, slams him against a wall and beats him in a display of the kind of violence that kept East Europeans in check most of the last four decades. Nov. 3-4: In <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> again, but East Germans are the drama. Thousands of them cram into the West German Embassy, another wave of East Germans heading West through <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Amid the jubilation, a prescient diplomat, scarcely believing he could be right, mutters, `` The wall has gone.'' Nov. 5: <PERSON> Pomezi </PERSON>, a Czech village sandwiched between East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. A chill dawn beside the dilapidated church. Scores of East German Trabant cars arrive at the border every hour, carrying their occupants away from a lifetime under communism. A <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION> worker tells how he got caught in the <LOCATION> Dresden </LOCATION> train station on the bloody night of Oct. 3-4 and saw riot police beating back thousands trying to get aboard trains carrying East Germans to the West. `` I saw them beat children,'' he says. `` That was when my wife and I decided to leave. We were always told the DDR -LRB- <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB- was a state of peace.'' Nov. 6: <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, in the rain. Another side of repression. In court, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, a Slovak dissident, facing up to 10 years in jail over just one article in an underground newspaper. Breaking through the barrier of fear that keeps most people far from the courtroom, a crowd of 200 gathers in the name of freedom under the watchful eyes of uniformed police and plainclothes officers who film them from the window. Later, activists talk warmly of the popular revolt in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Soon, soon, they say, it must come to <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. Nov. 9-10: East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. A night of delirium as the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall really does open. For this moment, there are no words. Car horns honk and people scream, weep and embrace. Even hardened <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> punkers have tears in their eyes. An East German family sharing my 2 a.m. taxi ride around a city they have n't seen for 28 years is dumbstruck. What the mother really could n't believe, as we inched our way through the Trabants around <ORGANIZATION> Bahnhof </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION>, was that fresh flowers were on sale in the middle of the night. Nov. 13: <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>. First taste of the center of the East German revolution, when 200,000 people roar across <LOCATION> Karl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marx </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, `` We are the people!'' Everyone is there _ young and old, religious believers and Communists, students and workers. `` I'll be here until we have free elections,'' says a 70-year-old woman, with the unbending Teutonic resolve that has powered the revolt. `` We are the generation that was most betrayed. Maybe the children will have it better.'' Nov. 17: <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>. New fears replace the old. An ethnic German family who abandoned a prosperous farm in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> 25 years ago sits at home, worrying. Will the opening of the borders mean a currency reform? `` We'll lose everything again,'' shudders the mother, two years away from a meager East German pension with only savings in East German marks to rely on. Nov. 20: <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> as people dreamed to see it ever since the day the 1968 `` Prague Spring'' was over, crushed by <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact troops and tanks. More than 100,000 people are on the streets saying `` No more!'' to police brutality and Stalinist rule. The procession is an explosion of Czech wit, pride and joy. A friend leaps toward me and his wife, hugging us tight with happiness. `` We made it,'' he cries. Nov. 24: <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> returns triumphantly to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> after 19 years in the political wilderness. On a balcony, <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> bows to the cheers, smiling broadly his hands outstretched in thanks. Then, he reaches toward the crowd and makes a movement as if to draw the 300,000 people to his breast. The vast crowd goes mad with joy. A day later, a photograph capturing the moment goes up in the windows of the state news agency. Nov. 27. Wenceslas Square is a sea of people and national flags and even the clocks stop for the noontime general strike, the biggest protest against 41 years of Communist rule. Hundreds of thousands sway like a huge soccer crowd as they derisively chant the name of <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepan </PERSON>, the sacked <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> party boss they blame for past police brutality. `` We'll be so happy if we can have back the people who had to leave this country,'' exults a villager from north <LOCATION> Bohemia </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> for the past week to drink in the most exciting days of the revolution. `` Everybody's expecting to spend Christmas together.'' `` What fascinates me,'' says a woman, `` is how all of a sudden people like each other.'' She is standing 50 feet from the spot where, just a month ago _ an era ago _ the policeman beat the Pole.
