<HEAD>House Panel Urges Federal Funds for Infertility Research</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> urged the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration Saturday to clear the way for use of federal funds for research into the infertility problem plaguing millions of American couples. Government unwillingness to fund research has slowed the search for ways to improve in vitro fertilization and other high-tech solutions to infertility, according to the report issued Saturday. In vitro fertilization, in which an egg is fertilized in a laboratory dish and then implanted in the womb, `` has changed from a rarely used technique to an established medical procedure'' over the last decade, the report said. But it added that `` only 6 percent of initial in vitro fertilization procedures result in the birth of a baby.'' About 2.4 million American couples can not have children because of infertility problems, the report said. Right to life groups have opposed infertility research because it involves studying fertilized eggs. Five Republicans on the 39-member committee disagreed with the report's recommendation, saying the issue goes beyond religion. They said `` hundreds of infertility clinics have been established across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as part of a billion-dollar industry serving people in need ... Given the strong private sector involvement in fighting infertility, perhaps this is not the best use of scarce tax dollars.'' The decision, in any case, should be made by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and not the administration, they said. For a decade, government funding for in vitro fertilization research has been caught in a bureaucratic tangle involving an <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> that first gave its approval, then went out of business and has never been reconstituted. The report recommended that research on in vitro fertilization be exempt from review by the board and instead be subject to approval by the director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. It also recommended that the board be reconstituted to pass judgment on other controversial research. The report said that as a result of the lack of effective treatment for infertility, many couples who can not conceive are `` exploited'' by health care professionals who claim to be specialists in the field but yield few successful pregnancies. A 1988 report by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> said that more than half of the 169 in vitro fertility clinics in existence at that time had not produced a live birth but patients were not told of their lack of success. Patients pay an average of $ 9,376 for two in vitro fertilization attempts, the report said. Additionally, because this is a method of last resort, these patients have already spent an average $ 13,000 on previous infertility treatments, it said. Most in vitro clinics have waiting lists of patients, some as long as one to two years, the report said. The report also recommended an increase in federal funding to prevent sexually transmitted diseases that cause infertility. The Centers for Disease Control estimates that 125,000 cases of infertility related to sexually transmitted diseases occur every year. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> also estimates that about half of these women want to have children. The report is based on an investigation by the human resources and intergovernmental relations subcommittee, which is chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and was issued by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
