<HEAD>Bush and Gorbachev Discuss Wide Range of Topics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf to UPDATE with weather-related delay in start-up
of afternoon round of talks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> began a storm-tossed summit today with five hours of talks, and the White House said afterward the two men worked in a `` spirit of forward-looking cooperation.'' The president and his Soviet counterpart `` recognized that economic and political challenges were ahead for <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and vowed to consider the opportunities presented with sensitivity and firm initiative,'' said the statement issued by <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. High winds and rough seas forced the two men to scrap plans to talk aboard a Soviet naval vessel anchored off-shore, opting instead for a session on a docked Soviet cruise liner that served as <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s headquarters for the two-day summit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> returned to his headquarters on the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belknap </ORGANIZATION> following the initial sessions. The White House said an afternoon round of talks were put on hold because of the bad weather, which kept <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> from immediately leaving the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>. The White House said they talked `` almost continuously'' for nearly five hours, including a session with aides and a session with only note-takers, and then continued their talks over lunch. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke for more than an hour to open the meeting, laying out more than a dozen ideas for economic and political progress in U.S.-Soviet relations,'' the statement said. `` The discussion ranged from the economic situation in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to arms control and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> spoke at length of perestroika and the goals of his reform program,'' it said. The two men also arranged to have an afternoon of talks before getting together for dinner. The summit concludes on Sunday. The White House said the opening talks included a ` ` very productive, informal and substantive meeting. `` The meetings were sparked by a spirit of forward-looking cooperation during these increasingly changing times,'' it said. The White House said the discussion ranged from the economic situation in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to arms control and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` Chairman <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> spoke at length of perestroika and the goals of his reform program,'' it said. `` The president emphasized his support for the success of perestroika. He set forth his ideas as a broad framework for actions that would help the two nations work together for peace and prosperity,'' it said. The two leaders, both in an affable mood, met aboard the 25,000-ton Maxim Gorky, which is <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s headquarters for the weekend summit, to begin nearly 12 hours of scheduled talks that could bring down the curtain on the Cold War. `` I think we've got a very good beginning of the dialogue ... an excellent beginning,'' Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told reporters after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> completed their initial three-hour session. Senior Soviet officials said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants the summit to produce a timetable for completing U.S.-Soviet treaties on reducing strategic nuclear weapons, conventional forces in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and chemical weapons. These officials, who spoke only on condition they not be identified, said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will convene a meeting of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leaders in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Monday to discuss the results of the two-day summit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will spend Monday briefing allied leaders at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> were smiling and in high spirits as they clasped hands across a long rectangular table, measuring barely a yard across. `` It's so narrow that if we do n't have enough arguments, we'll kick each other,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Asked by reporters if they would reach any agreements, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> replied, `` da, da -LRB- yes, yes -RRB-.'' Agreement on what? he was asked. `` Mnogovo,'' which was translated as meaning `` a lot of things.'' When <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was asked the same question, the president echoed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` Mnogovo,'' he said. The two leaders met in the plush surroundings of a library-like room known as the Card Room, next to the ship's lounge and nightclub, on the Maxim Gorky's promenade deck. They sat in deep captain's chairs, accompanied by aides on either side. Arms control, East-West trade and the breathtaking democratic reforms sweeping communist <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> dominated the agenda for the Bush-Gorbachev talks. Both leaders said they hoped their discussions would strengthen long-term prospects for world peace and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> unity. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, asked if he would discuss fast-moving political changes in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, replied, `` We'll be discussing everything, including that.'' The senior Soviet sources said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants a Stategic Arms Reduction Treaty ready for signing at his next planned summit meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next spring or early summer. They said the Soviet leader also is seeking a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> commitment to attend a 35-nation summit at the end of 1990 to sign a separate accord sharply reducing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet troops in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The original site for the first summit session was the Soviet guided missile cruiser Slava, anchored near the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON> in this harbor, but White House officials said the meeting was shifted to the Maxim Gorky because gale-force winds would have made launch transfers treacherous. The White House said `` there was no danger to anyone aboard <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON> as a result of the high winds.'' The 630-foot <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> is about twice as large as the Slava in total tonnage. Built 20 years ago in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, it was sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1974 and is used frequently for cruises through the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and Scandanavian waters. The vessel was repaired after it rammed an iceberg off <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> last June with 900 people aboard, but there were no injuries. The two leaders are scheduled to meet Sunday aboard the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>, flagship of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sixth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> which is anchored about 400 yards from the Slava.
