<HEAD>Gale Winds Force Change in Summit Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with second session delayed; picks up 4th graf
pvs, ``Maltese meteorologist xxx'' Edits to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winds gusting to 48 miles per hour and roiling seas moved the first summit session between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to a Soviet luxury liner and delayed the second round of meetings. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> met this morning on the 25,000-ton liner Maxim Gorky after gale-force winds caused both the Soviet ship Slava, the original site of today's meeting, and the USS Belknap to drag their anchors. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> returned to <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON> after five hours of talks and was to return to the Gorky for an afternoon summit session. But the White House said the weather forced a delay in that second session. This morning, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement saying that the winds, which built overnight, `` make it difficult to disembark from launches at the Slava and the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>. Therefore, this morning's meeting has been shifted to the Soviet ship Gorky at anchor at <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>. Maltese meteorologist <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Agius </PERSON> said the winds should abate by Sunday, the final day of the summit. `` It will definitely be improving tomorrow,'' he said. Despite a little pitching from the heavy seas, the winds did not present a danger to anyone on the <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s headquarters for the summit and the site of his wrap-up meeting on Sunday with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the White House statement said. In fact, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who slept aboard the Belknap Friday night, said on the <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> that he was `` feeling pretty good.'' Asked how he slept, he said, `` fine, just fine ... piece of cake.'' The stormy conditions prompted <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to delay a sightseeing tour, but she later went ahead with the visit, including an inspection of a 16th-century cathedral. `` This is the type of weather that shipwrecked Saint <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> on these rocks. We usually have this in February,'' <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassar </PERSON>, Maltese minister for housing, told a rain-soaked crowd that had gathered to see the Soviet leader's wife at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, a suburb of <LOCATION> Valletta </LOCATION>, the capital city. Both the 12,500-ton Slava and 8,600-ton <PERSON> Belknap </PERSON> are anchored in the middle of the Bay, while the much larger Gorky, which has been <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s base during his time in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, is tied up at a pier. The high winds were blowing from the northeast. <PERSON> Marsaxlokk </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON>, a large indentation in the southeast coast of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, is exposed to winds from easterly directions. The hasty change in plans for the superpower meeting in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> came as the tiny wind-whipped island nation was as ready as it would ever be for its weekend in the international limelight. <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> was hoping the summit would boost attention for the island, but the bad weather probably was not the type of publicity the Maltese had in mind. On shore, red Soviet flags flapped in the stiff breeze. On Friday, street salesmen were out in force to hawk commemorative T-shirts and other souvenir and residents strolled to the edge of <LOCATION> Marsaxlokk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> for a look at the two anchored warships. `` This may help your tourism,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had told Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenech-Adami </PERSON> on Friday following his arrival from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` It will probably bring positive economic effects,'' said a 21-year-old woman who identified herself only as <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON>, assessing the summit's meaning for the 350,000 Maltese. She and two companions had come out Friday night for a glimpse of the warships. `` We were bored,'' she admitted. On the other side of the bay, in the fishing village of <LOCATION> Birzebuga </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> led a group of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> workers preparing for a peace demonstration timed to coincide with the summit, decorating a float that will be a part of a 60-piece parade on Saturday. `` Give peace a chance,'' said signs on the float in both English and Russian. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> were unlikely to see the parade itself, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said: `` <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> is ready to show to the world that we hope for peace.'' Traffic circles and seaside roads were decorated with Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags, and Maltese security forces stood through the night in clumps of two or three on streets overlooking the harbor. <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>'s entire 1,200-man military and most of its 1,000 police officers have been assigned to the summit security job. Roadblocks and checkpoints made it hard to get around on the narrow island roads, although it seemed anyone with a good story could get waved through. Although thousands of Maltese had skipped work or classes to catch a glimpse of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s arrival early Friday, most were already in bed by the time <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s Il-62 rolled up to the airport gangway at 11 p.m. sharp during a gentle mist. The prime minister and his cabinet broke from their line and walked over to the plane's gangplank as Sgt. <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gatt </PERSON>, a 32-veteran of the Maltese army, and two other soldiers rolled out a red carpet for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>, who walked arm-in-arm down the steps. After a 21-gun salute, a Maltese armed forces band in dark blue uniforms with red piping on their pants played the Soviet and Maltese national anthems. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> thanked <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> for preparing the summit for him and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Although we will be meeting on naval ships, I would like to assure you that we will be speaking about peace, about how we can work for a better world,'' he said.
