<HEAD>13 Years Later, New Probe Launched in Reporter's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT referenct to husband to ex-husband;
recasts 18th graf, `And some...' to CLARIFY jealousy theory.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 13 years after a car bomb killed an investigative reporter for <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s largest newspaper, the murder case has been reopened even though the motive is as murky as ever. When Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> leans back and puts his cowboy boots on the desk in his Old West-style office, he can choose from a tangle of theories about who ordered the death of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> reporter <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>. There's the mob. Casinos. Race track owners. Bankers. Even a jealous ex-husband. And there are plots within plots. One theory is that the hit men collected twice, from different people. So far, though, only one man has been convicted, and the masterminds, whoever they were, remain free. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>, a Republican whose office comes up for election next year, has been attacked by potential challengers for not solving the case. But he insists those attacks were not a factor in his decision to reinstate a murder charge last week against <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Robison </PERSON>, a plumber accused of setting off the bomb. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> says he has `` new evidence'' but wo n't say what it is or where it points. `` You do n't need motive for a conviction,'' he said. `` It helps ... but I do n't need to show motive.'' <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>, 47, died 11 days after the radio-controlled bomb blew up his car in a hotel parking lot in June 1976. As he lay dying, he was heard to say `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>,'' `` Emprise'' and `` Mafia.'' <ORGANIZATION> Emprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, now known as <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, was a partner with the Funk family of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> in dog-racing tracks. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>, 45, who ultimately became the only man convicted in the case so far, was a greyhound breeder and tow-truck operator who drank heavily and used cocaine. <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON> had left a note at his desk saying he was planning to meet him to discuss a land-fraud scheme involving high-level politicians. At trial, <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> testified in return for leniency, saying he planted the car bomb and <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> triggered it on orders from <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON>, a man trying to ingratiate himself with land and liquor magnate <PERSON> Kemper </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>, a target of <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>' stories, was never charged with the crime, however, and an appeals court threw out the <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON> convictions. <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON> was released, though <PERSON> Robison </PERSON>, 67, remains in prison on an unrelated assault conviction. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> decided to drop charges against <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON> when <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> refused to testify in a retrial unless he got a better deal than he originally bargained for. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>, arguing that <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> had broken the plea bargain, brought him to trial and won a murder conviction and death sentence he hoped would persuade <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> to talk. A federal appeals court threw out <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON>'s death sentence earlier this year, however, and <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> filed a new murder charge against <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> last week without waiting for further appeals to be heard by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. A preliminary hearing is scheduled for January. Separately, a state grand jury is investigating potential obstruction of justice charges and has called in witnesses that could fit several of the scenarios. Several people, including free-lance reporter <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Devereux </PERSON>, have theorized that <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON> may have been killed because he was investigating industrial gold thefts and their ties to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> bankers. <PERSON> Devereux </PERSON> and others have suggested <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON> was looking at dog-track skimming, however, and they cite his dying words. Still others have linked the death to a `` Mafia diary'' that describes casino skimming, but that some contend is a forgery. And some, including <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> at one time, have pointed to a member of the Funk family as a `` contingency suspect,'' saying he resented his ex-wife's closeness with <PERSON> Bolles </PERSON>, whom she confided in. Some of the theories overlap, and there are those who believe the hit men may have been paid originally by one person before persuading a second who did n't know about the first contract to pay for it too. <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> declined to be interviewed last week, and <PERSON> Robison </PERSON> referred a reporter to his attorney, who did not return calls. The reopening of the case pleased those close to <LOCATION> Bolles </LOCATION>. His brother <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, an author, said: `` I'd just like to know the truth.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Bolles </LOCATION> colleague who still covers the case, said: `` You at least have some activity going on in the case.''
