<HEAD>Taiwan Voters Given A Choice, Ask Gods For Advice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Taiwan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the Sea Goddess Temple on Saturday, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ying-shi </PERSON> tossed the wood blocks once, twice, three times. `` That's it,'' said the grizzled fisherman. `` Sea Goddess says no voting today.'' As he hobbled away, a young woman in a blue dress took his place in front of the altar, facing an image of the fetching goddess. `` I've never voted before,'' she said with a shy smile after tossing the blocks, a Buddhist ritual. `` I needed advice.'' Indeed, for the first time in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s history, a legal opposition party has given voters something close to real choice in the first nationwide elections since martial law was lifted in 1987. Long lines formed at polling booths throughout the island. `` We've been going full steam since 8 a.m.,'' said one police officer at a polling station near the Sea Goddess Temple in northern <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>. `` It's just getting busier.'' As he spoke, three elderly women moved slowly out of the voting booth. `` We choose the opposition,'' said one, as she stood between her two sisters clutching their hands. `` We talked about it last night and decided to vote our mind. The people must speak.'' The opposition, or <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, ran a spirited campaign against the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has governed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> since 1949 when it fled mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after losing a civil war to the Communists. The <ORGANIZATION> DPP </ORGANIZATION> finds its strength mostly among the Taiwanese working class who were here when the mainlanders came over from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The opposition portrayed the Nationalists as corrupt, accusing them of vote-buying and using state-run television to push Nationalist candidates. The Nationalists depicted the opposition as a chaotic band of radicals, ready to proclaim <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s cultural and political independence from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The issue was an emotional one because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has warned it could attack <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> if this island of 20 million proclaims independence. It also cut to the heart of the Nationalists claim on power. Ever since fleeing to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, the Nationalists have said they alone are the legitimate government of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, an 83-year-old retired <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> official, fled to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1948 to help set up a government for the beleagured Nationalists and their leader <PERSON> Generalissimo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Kai-shek </PERSON>. After years of supporting <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON>'s martial law policies, <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> said he now he supports political liberalization. `` But slowly, slowly,'' he said, banging his cane on the pavement. His grandson, <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yin-lien </PERSON> agreed. `` Instability is a bad thing,'' said the 25-year-old law student who voted for the Nationalists with his grandfather in western <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>. `` We want calm for <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>.'' Their viewpoint is common among <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s people, strongly influenced by Confucian ethics that worship harmony. Still, some voters said they did n't agree. `` A little turmoil may not be a bad thing,'' said one voter after casting his ballot for the opposition. `` It's like marriage. If you do n't argue, you never make up.''
