<HEAD>Delay Reported in Start of Search for Lost Commuter Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The search for a commuter plane that disappeared off <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> last week was delayed at least 20 minutes until somebody at the Westerly airport noticed it was late, a newspaper reported Saturday. Eight people were aboard when the plane presumably crashed into Block Island Sound while flying the 17 miles from the island to Westerly on Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> gave up searching for survivors Wednesday night after finding debris and two dead dogs from the plane. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> officials said investigators had not recovered the plane, but were compiling various evidence, including records showing the aircraft underwent extensive repairs for a crack three years ago. Officials planned to use sonar Monday to scan the ocean floor for debris. New England Airlines President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendokas </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal-Bulletin </ORGANIZATION> the search was delayed because ticket agents at Westerly did not realize the flight had not arrived until 7 p.m., when they called him at home and said it was 20 minutes overdue. The pilots commonly fuel and unload planes before checking in with the terminal desk, he said. <PERSON> Bendokas </PERSON> said he called the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> at 7:15 p.m., alhough <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> center at Quonset Point, said his logs show the call coming in at 7:35 p.m. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> records from the agency's <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> office indicate the airplane underwent repairs for a crack on July 1, 1986. Seventeen separate steps were taken to fix the hole, said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON>. `` The company was doing more maintenance than required by the manufacturer'' on the 1969 model <PERSON> Britten-Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Islander </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> said an examination of a dog that was accompanying one of the missing passengers indicated the animal drowned. He would not speculate whether that meant the airplane broke up when it hit the water. Seas were 5 to 6 feet and water temperatures about 45 degrees, making survival unlikely for anyone in the water. The plane was not tracked on air traffic control radar and there were no radio calls for help before the crash, <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. Since older commuter planes normally do n't carry the `` black box'' flight recorders that are on larger commercial airliners, the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> said investigators were piecing together other evidence, including the pilot's background. Pilot <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 46, had flown part-time for the airline for about six months, <PERSON> Bendokas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> previously flew for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and for about 10 years with area charter operations, he said.
