<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet spokesmen expressed satisfaction Saturday after five hours of talks in which <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> advocated a quicker timetable for completion of nuclear and conventional arms treaties next year and edged toward a chemical arms deal. `` Things went well,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> told reporters who waited in vain aboard the Soviet passenger liner <PERSON> Maksim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> for an afternoon session. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was forced to postpone the meeting and a dinner because gale force winds prevented him from leaving the USS Belknap, anchored a few hundreds yards offshore from the Gorky, which was tied ashore. `` They talked about everything, arms, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, philosophical questions,'' <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said of the morning and luncheon talks. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> suggested that the two men meet again in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the last two weeks of June, said a White House offical who spoke on condition of anonymity. And the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president reiterated his commitment, which is shared by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, that they should use the occasion to sign a treaty to slash superpower strategic nuclear aresenals by 30 to 50 percent, to 6,000 warheads apiece. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> planned to brief his <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> allies Monday in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on the summit, said Soviet officials, but it was unclear whether problems with the weather here would delay that meeting. For the first time, a non-communist _ Polish Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> _ likely will sit around the table with <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leaders. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was pressing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for greater speed on the strategic arms treaty, said <PERSON> Vitaly </PERSON> <PERSON> Churkin </PERSON>, a spokesman for Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also wanted a commitment from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to attend a proposed 35-nation summit of <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> leaders in late 1990 to sign a pact, now under negotiation, to remove 30,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and 325,000 Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The White House spokesmen said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had proposed completing the deal and signing it at a summit of the 23 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance members at a summit in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, last next year. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also appeared successful in prodding <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> toward an agreement to curb or eliminate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet chemical weapons. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in September that the superpowers cut their chemical arms by 80 percent, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue to produce a new generation of chemical weapons. The bilateral treaty would be intended to build momentum for a 40-nation accord to eliminate chemical weapons over 10 years. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would destroy all its chemical arms by that deadline if all chemical-capable nations did likewise and signed the accord, but administation officials that American would retain 2 percent of its stockpiles through the 10th year. The White House official said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> now was willing to drop the idea of continuing chemical weapons production, and that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would stop making a new generation of chemical weapons as soon as a multi-lateral agreement to ban such weapons take effect. The leaders also agreed to schedule two or three arms control meetings between between Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, the first in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in January and the next at a multinational meeting in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> in February. A Soviet media commentator, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, said it was possible that the summit would stretch into late Sunday to cope with the interruption Saturday, but stressed he was not speaking for the Kremlin. Such a delay might force postponement of the planned meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact leaders, convening amid sweeping changes in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that the Soviet officials said would require a restructuring of the Soviet-led military alliance, which was formed in 1955 in response to the creation of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. In the past, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other Soviet leaders have met with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders of the six <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> members, but the dissolution of the Hungarian party and the creation of a Solidarity-led government in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has complicated the process, said the officials. `` It is now up to the countries to decide who to send to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>,'' said a Soviet official. `` It will be the bosses as usual.'' <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, for example, is likely to send President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, and <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, the Solidarity official who last August formed the first non-Communist government in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION>. The communists retain control of the defense and internal security minstries. The reorganization of the alliance, however, will not be settled Monday. `` It's a hot period now. We need to wait until the situation sorts itself out in these countries,'' said one official. `` The future of the blocs must be discussed'' by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said the official, who minimized talk of a reunified <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> along the lines proposed last week by German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>. `` They should work on the basis of two Germanies for the foreseeable future,'' said the official. `` That means as long as you can see.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he will not negotiate the future of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.
