<HEAD>Investigation Clouds Image as Medical Association Meets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Making the ...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
AMA trustees saying Sammons acted within his authority, proposing outside
auditor, CORRECT that Sammons is widely admired, sted was; picks up 8th
graf, `In 1987 ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> prepare to meet to set policy on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health-care issues, some members are questioning how well the group is running itself after recent revelations about money-losing deals. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> is coping with a controversy involving an executive's pension losses in a high-risk stock market fund and a loan to another executive who defaulted The disclosures have shaken the conservative image of the Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>, which with 300,000 members is the nation's largest organization for doctors `` It's a huge embarrassment to us, to the profession and to the organization,'' said one <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> doctor and <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> member who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` We are concerned about our image because so much of medicine is based on trust.'' A resolution calling for the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s top executive to step aside during an investigation is expected to go this week to the group's <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> The policy-setting body is meeting in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> Sunday through Wednesday to consider a host of other issues as well, including patients' rights and funding for AIDS care. Last month, four <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> affiliates passed resolutions concerning revelations that Executive Vice President Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> had approved two money-losing deals for other top association executives. Making the matter even more painful, doctors say, is that <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> is widely admired within the association as an eloquent and effective spokesman and has been credited with saving the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> from financial disaster when he took the job in 1974. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION>, after receiving a report from the law firm doing the investigation, issued its own report Saturday concluding <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> had `` acted within the scope of his authority.'' The report, which will go to delegates for ratification this week, also said the board will restructure its committees and hire a new outside auditing firm to try to provide the type of accountability sought in the affiliates' resolutions. The trustees declined to comment on the report. In 1987, <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> approved a $ 353,000 reimbursement to Chief Operating Officer <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Strobhar </PERSON> for losses he suffered in the `` Black Monday'' stock market crash. <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> said he ordered the reimbursement after <PERSON> Strohbar </PERSON> reported that his $ 1.4 million in pension funds was moved by mistake from relatively safe money-market funds to high-risk but potentially more lucrative investments. Two years later, <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> reversed his decision after <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> attorneys said the transfer of funds before the Oct. 19, 1987, market crash was not a mistake but a `` deliberate act.'' When the deal was reported in a <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> investigation in October, <PERSON> Strobhar </PERSON>, 57, resigned and agreed to repay with interest what he acknowledged was an `` inappropriate'' reimbursement. In the second deal, the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 50,000 on a $ 267,000 loan <PERSON> Sammons </PERSON> approved in May 1985 to help another top executive buy a luxury condominium while he was going through a divorce. <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> K