<HEAD>Oak Ridge Sales Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it was resuming commercial sale of a key component of nuclear warheads after concluding that amounts listed as missing had n't been stolen after all. The material, tritium, has been sold for 25 years in small amounts for research and for making glow-in-the-dark markings, as for clock faces, exit signs and airport runway markings in remote areas. It is also used to boost the power of nuclear warheads and the power thermonuclear weapons. Twice this year, the Department suspended commercial shipments from the <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. The first time followed complaints of customers that they had not received as much as 40 percent of the material they were billed for; the second time, in October, followed the loss of a substantial fraction from a trial shipment designed to test handling procedures. The department's announcement late Friday of the resumption of shipments said: `` Four investigations of the tritium shipping discrepancies have found no evidence to support the possibility of theft or diversion ... Among the causes of the discrepancies were deficiencies in equipment, measurement methods, procedures, records and management and technical oversight'' as well as the unique properties of tritium. Department spokesman <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Keif </PERSON> said he was unable to assign a percentage of the 5 grams listed as missing from commercial shipments to the reasons given, but `` We think it is explainable'' by those reasons. `` We do n't think tritium was stolen,'' <PERSON> Keif </PERSON> said. Tritium is a radioactive form of hydrogen, notoriously difficult to confine in piping and containers. Officials said in October they believed undetected leaks could be one cause of the missing material. The department said it had revised its measurement techniques and saw no need to revise its handling regulations. The nation's tritium production and inventories are secret, but there have been estimates that only about 4 grams is needed for a plutonium-powered warhead.
