<SECOND>AM-Crane Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crane Crash Investigators Zero in on `Dead Man's' Switch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling throughout to Fairburn, sted Fairbanks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators want to know why the `` dead man's switch'' failed on a crane, letting tons of steel pour down on a busy street and killing five people, a state official said Friday. `` The brakes on the crane are its dead man's switch,'' said <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION>, deputy chief of the state <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` It takes energy to release brakes.'' The crane's cab made a sudden 180 degree turn Tuesday as the crane's height was being increased from 16 to 20 stories at the construction site of a new high-rise. There have been published reports that the crane's operator, who was among those killed, had a history of alcohol problems and also suggestions that he may have suffered a heart attack. The crane is being studied by experts, but <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION> said going over the wreckage would not be a quick job. The crane, capable of lifting 177 tons, had to be perfectly balanced during the repositioning operation, according to <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, a vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Swinerton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Walberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the general contractor for the project. Despite the necessary balancing, both <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION> and company officials agreed that repositioning a crane is not considered dangerous. `` No one in our firm has ever seen or heard of an incident where a crane collapsed while being raised from one position to another,'' said <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, the firm's chairman. `` Historically, it's a very safe operation,'' said <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION>. Both government and company investigators are trying to find out why the cab suddenly went out of control. `` The crane's dead-man arrangement is n't like it is on a motorcycle,'' said the investigator. `` There, it's the throttle. You let go, it shuts off. With brakes that are locked in place, you have to take deliberate action.'' He said investigators must find out `` whether it was released by the operator or if there was some malfunction.'' Right now, he said, the probe is focusing on human error. <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION> said he is aware of published reports that crane operator <PERSON> Lonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> had a history that included alcohol and drug abuse. `` We have expanded our investigation to look into that and have asked the coroner to speed the toxicology report. The alcohol concerns me because of the psychological and physiological problems associated with it,'' he said. Coroner's officials have said blood alcohol test results will be available in about two weeks. There also has been speculation that <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> may have suffered a heart attack. <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>' sister, <ORGANIZATION> Genoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hefke </ORGANIZATION>, said she spoke with a worker who was on the ground and in radio contact with <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON> before the accident. She said the worker told her that the radio suddenly went silent and that <PERSON> Boggess </PERSON>, 45, may have had a heart attack. `` All of a sudden he stopped answering, and then it started rocking back and forth,'' she said. But, said <LOCATION> Fairburn </LOCATION>, a heart attack would n't account for the cab suddenly going out of control. `` Even if he had a heart attack and slumped forward, it is relatively safe because the brakes are locked up. They have guards on them so you ca n't slump over them. Again, it would take deliberate action to release them.''
