<HEAD>For Release Monday, Dec. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Muni Bonds in Moscow? Consultant Trying To Point the Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Is <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> ready for muni bonds? An American financial consultant is trying to find that out. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> has signed an agreement with Soviet officials to help develop the concept of public bond financing in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> says his plan is aimed at giving Soviet residents a place to put their huge savings of rubles and at the same time aid the rebuilding of the nation's economy. Any bond program would have to overcome intense skepticism on the part of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people, but <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> believes it is worth a try. `` The whole essence of the program is to put the ruble to work,'' he said in an interview last week. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, 37, runs a consulting firm in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and used to be chief of staff for Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Democrat. Last summer he directed government affairs for the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Peace Festival, a rock concert. He is not to be confused with the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor of the same name who advises Latin American debtor nations and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s Solidarity movement. The president of <ORGANIZATION> Jeffrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said he developed his contacts with Soviet officials while helping set up the Make a <ORGANIZATION> Difference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> concert, whose proceeds went to programs fighting drug and alcohol abuse. `` I realized that in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, public finance is a very logical place to begin developing an investment banking system _ everything is government there,'' he said. He said the Soviets were taken with the idea, including ones from the influential Institute of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> in September, <PERSON> Georgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, the institute's director and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said the biggest concern was the non-convertibility of the ruble into hard Western currencies. To tailor public finance bonds to Soviet investors _ who may not be attracted by the prospect of earning more rubles, since there is little to buy with them _ <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> proposes that the bonds pay interest in the form of foreign currency certificates. These certificates could be spent in the country's hard-currency shops. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> also suggested to the Soviets that they create a savings bond program, which would pay interest in rubles rather than hard currencies. Such an issue would need to address concerns about inflation and compensate for any devaluations in the ruble, <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> said, in order to attract Soviet investors. These bonds would leverage the vast amounts of rubles Soviet citizens have salted away, and be a good use of the country's scarce hard currency, <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said Under the `` protocol of intentions'' <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> signed last month <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials, including <PERSON> Arbatov </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> agreed to assemble a group of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic and investment advisers to help devise a demonstration project using a bond issue. Possibilities under consideration include housing, a manufacturing plant and a hospital. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said he has had preliminary discussions with several Wall Street firms, which he declined to identify. He said the protocol is the first step in a process that is expected to lead to a joint-venture agreement with the Soviets. The protocol, which also was signed by the deputy chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, states that `` the development of a system of public finance in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is a critical component of economic reform.'' One expert on the Soviet economy was skeptical of <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>'s proposals `` Bonds have a bad reputation among the Soviet people,'' said <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brada </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor. <PERSON> Brada </PERSON> said Soviets were soured on bonds by a Stalin-era bond program used to help finance the government. `` Everyone had to buy these bonds. They hated it,'' he said in a telephone interview. The bonds were repudiated by <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, who said the government would not make payments on them. <PERSON> Brada </PERSON> said Soviets also would question any plan to index a bond's return to inflation or currency changes. `` People see that real inflation is much higher than what the state's index shows,'' he said. `` No one is going to believe that the indexing is going to be done honestly.'' <PERSON> Brada </PERSON> believes a better way to improve the Soviet economy would be to devalue the ruble sharply and make it convertible into Western currencies.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
