<FIRST>r f BC-U-Haul-Ryder     12-02 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-U-Haul-Ryder,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies U-Haul Motion in Suit Against Ryder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGER SANDAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge on Friday denied Phoenix-based <ORGANIZATION> U-Haul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s request to order 2,500 of a competitor's biggest trucks off the road U-Haul had asked Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for a preliminary injunction against <ORGANIZATION> Ryder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, claiming that Miami-based Ryder had equipped a fleet of 24-foot rental trucks with a loading device similar to one U-Haul patented Jan. 30, 1973. The patent expires Jan. 30, 1990. The patented device, U-Haul maintained, gives its trucks a competitive advantage of having lower rear decks, making them easier for consumers to load and unload. Ryder told the judge it would suffer an $ 8 million loss in the fourth quarter if it had to remove its trucks from the marketplace. The trucks were introduced in early 1989. Both sides claimed victory Friday. `` It was very favorable to the U-Haul patent,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, an attorney for U-Haul. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> refused to issue the injunction largely because the `` damage to Ryder, by having all 2,500 of its infringing trucks parked, outweighed U-Haul's need for such a short injunction.'' `` We are gratified that the court has so far supported Ryder's position,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Ryder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Truck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rental </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement Ryder contends it did not infringe on U-Haul's patent. The 2,500 trucks, which each cost about $ 30,000, represent about 8 percent of Ryder's fleet of consumer rental vehicles, Ryder said. U-Haul on Aug. 23 filed a patent-infringement suit against Ryder, and on Sept. 15 filed for the preliminary injunction asking that the trucks be taken off the road. A trial has yet to be scheduled in the case, but is expected to go before <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON> during the first half of 1990.
</TEXT>
