<FIRST>d f PM-SIA     12-02 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SIA,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Industry Group Proposals Ending Barrier With Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street leaders have declared an end to their lengthy battle to keep banks out of the stocks and bonds business, proposing to repeal the law that has governed the nation's basic banking structure since the Depression. Directors of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, at the trade group's annual convention here, on Friday endorsed a proposal for new legislation to let subsidiaries of banks `` engage in a broad range of securities and securities-related activities.'' At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> said its plan would let brokers engage in consumer banking businesses and join banks in having access to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s banking system, including the right to borrow from the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> in emergencies. The move appears to herald one of the biggest breaks yet in the gradually crumbling wall separating banking and brokerage activities, erected by the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 amid the financial crisis that followed the stock market crash four years earlier. The barrier has been weakened chink by chink in recent years, with the move toward financial deregulation and court decisions permitting banks to make increasing inroads into what had formerly been the brokers' turf. For example, many banks now participate in new offerings of some kinds of securities, offer discount stock brokerage and sell shares in mutual funds. Brokers, for their part, have also successfully launched forays into businesses once considered the domain of the banks. In 1977, for example, they began to offer `` central assets accounts'' that are technically not bank deposits, but come with such features as check-writing, credit cards and lines of credit. The banking industry itself has used such brokerage services as an argument for dismantling Glass-Steagall and allowing them greater authority to enter the securities, insurance and real estate businesses. Nevertheless, brokers have until now consistently sought to hold the Glass-Steagall line, arguing that banks would enjoy several unfair advantages in any arena of unfettered competition. They also say banks, with their federal deposit insurance and links to the Federal Reserve System, should not be allowed to expose themselves to risky ventures involving such things as the sale of stocks. <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> officials said that banking groups played no part in formulating their plan, which was made after a lengthy board meeting late Friday. <PERSON> Hardwick </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION>, the outgoing chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates Wall Street, had been consulted and indicated that it `` applauded the initiative.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> said it would be holding talks with the next few weeks with the <ORGANIZATION> Bush </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and regulators to work out details of what could amount to one of the most sweeping changes in basic financial legislation in 56 years. One widely discussed possible result of any Glass-Steagall reform has been mergers between the biggest banks and brokerage firms. <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> did not address such specifics. However, most observers point out that after any merger banking and brokerage activities still would have to be conducted by separate subsidiaries of the same company because brokers are regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> while banking is regulated by a different set of agencies, including the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, Comptroller of the Currency and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` We think that anything that leads to vastly increased financial concentration is not in the broader interests of our financial system,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which represents thousands of community banks. Asked about the late-afternoon development, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said executives at the nation's largest banking company would want to study the full resolution. But he added, `` It's been a bad month for walls.'' Outside observers see a variety of possible motives for the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION>'s change of strategy. Some believe that influential members of the securities business felt it was useless and costly to keep fighting pitched battles, a good many of which were being lost. Also, the proposal comes at a time when brokers are confronted with a barrage of other problems, including high overhead and shrinking profits from many of their traditional activities. When one prominent Wall Street figure, Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutfreund </PERSON> of the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, spoke to the convention on Thursday, he declared: `` It is time for all the institutions in the financial services industry to find some common ground.'' A major mission facing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> financial institutions, he said, is to `` work to design the post-Glass-Steagall world.''
</TEXT>
